[
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 1"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Evaluate the following limit: $ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 4} \\frac {2x^3-128} {\\sqrt{x}-2} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "To answer this question, first rationalize the limit: "
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 4} \\frac {2x^3-128} {\\sqrt{x}-2} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 4} \\frac {2x^3-128} {\\sqrt{x}-2} \\times \\frac {\\sqrt{x}+2} {\\sqrt{x}+2}$"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 4} \\frac {2(x^3-64)(\\sqrt{x}+2)} {x-4} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 4} \\frac {2(x^3-(4)^3)(\\sqrt{x}+2)} {x-4} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 4} \\frac {2(x-4)(x^2+4x+16)(\\sqrt{x}+2)} {x-4} \\quad $ by using difference of cubes"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 4} \\frac {2 \\cancel{(x-4)} (x^2+4x+16)(\\sqrt{x}+2)} {\\cancel{x-4}} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 4} \\ 2(x^2+4x+16)(\\sqrt{x}+2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = 2((4)^2+4(4)+16)(\\sqrt{(4)}+2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = 2(16+16+16)(2+2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = 384 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 2"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Solve the following limit: $ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -27} \\frac {27 + x} {x^{\\frac {1} {3}} + 3} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Looks like we need to substitute some values:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Let $ n = x^{\\frac {1} {3}} \\ \\Rightarrow \\ n^3 = x $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "We also need to know at what value $n$ should approach:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ n = (-27)^{\\frac {1} {3}} = -3 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now let's simply substitute and solve:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{n \\to -3} \\frac {27 + n^3} {n + 3} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{n \\to -3} \\frac {(n + 3)(n^2 - 3n + 9)} {n + 3} \\quad $ By difference of cubes"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{n \\to -3} \\frac {\\cancel{(n + 3)}(n^2 - 3n + 9)} {\\cancel{n + 3}} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{n \\to -3} (n^2 - 3n + 9) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ (-3)^2 - 3(-3) + 9 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ 9 + 9 + 9 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ 27 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 3"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Is the function $ f(x) $ continuous? Use limits to justify your answer."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(x) = \\left \\{\\begin {matrix} \\sqrt {2x + 1}, \\quad x \\ge 4 \\newline \\frac {1} {2} x + 3, \\quad -2 < x < 4 \\newline (x + 3)^2 + 1, \\quad x \\le -2 \\end{matrix} \\right. $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "At $ x = -2 $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(-2) = ((-2) + 3)^2 + 1 = 1 + 1 = 2 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -2^-} f(x) = ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -2^-} (x + 3)^2 + 1 = ((-2) + 3)^2 + 1 = 1 + 1 = 2 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -2^+} f(x) = ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -2^+} \\frac {1} {2} x + 3 = \\frac {1} {2} (-2) + 3 = -1 + 3 = 2 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(-2) = ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -2^-} f(x) = ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -2^+} f(x) \\ \\Rightarrow \\ $ f(x) is continuous at $ x = -2 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "At $ x = 4 $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(4) = \\sqrt {2(4) + 1} = \\sqrt {9} = 3 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -4^-} f(x) = \\frac {1} {2} x + 3 = \\frac {1} {2} (4) + 3 = 2 + 3 = 5 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -4^+} f(x) = ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -4^+} \\sqrt {2x + 1} = \\sqrt {2(4) + 1} = \\sqrt {9} = 3 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(x) = ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -4^+} \\ne ^{\\lim}_{x \\to -4^-} \\ \\Rightarrow \\ f(x) $ is discontinuous at $ x = 4 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore $ The function $ f(x) $ is not continuous."
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 4"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Find the value of $k$ for which the limit exists: $ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {4x^2+kx+7k-6} {2x^2-5x-3} $, and then evaluate that limit."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "This question is quite tough to get at first glance, however, if we factor out the denominator, it becomes a bit more clear:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {4x^2+kx+7k-6} {2x^2-5x-3} = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {4x^2+kx+7k-6} {(x-3)(2x+1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "As you can see, the $ (x-3) $ term results in the limit's function being undefined at $ x=3 $, so we need to somehow factor it out."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "To factor out the $ (x-3) $ term, the numerator must have it as one of its factors. This means that $ x=3 $ is a root of $ 4x^2+kx+7k-6 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "So, to find the value of $k$, we plug in $ x=3 $ and set the equation equal to $0$:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 4x^2+kx+7k-6 = 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 4(3)^2+k(3)+7k-6 = 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 36+10k-6 = 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 10k = -30 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ k = -3 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now, we need to evaluation the limit using $ k=-3 $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {4x^2+kx+7k-6} {(x-3)(2x+1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {4x^2+(-3)x+7(-3)-6} {(x-3)(2x+1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {4x^2-3x-27} {(x-3)(2x+1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {(x-3)(4x+9)} {(x-3)(2x+1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {\\cancel{(x-3)} (4x+9)} {\\cancel{(x-3)} (2x+1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 3} \\frac {4x+9} {2x+1} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\frac {4(3)+9} {2(3)+1} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ = \\frac {21} {7} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 5"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Use limits to determine the value of $k$ and $m$ for the function below such that the limit exists at $x=1$ but the function is discontinuous at this point."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$f(x) = \\left \\{\\begin{matrix} kx-2, \\quad x < 1 \\newline -mx^2, \\quad x = 1 \\newline -x^3+2m, \\quad x>1 \\end{matrix}\\right.$"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Since $f(x)$ is discontinuous at $x=1$, then $f(x) \\neq \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 1} f(x) $."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Use the left or right limit to determine a value for which $m$ or $k$ is not equal to (we used the left limit):"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ -mx^2 \\neq \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 1^{+}} (-x^3 + 2m) \\quad $ ( $f(x)$ at $x=1$ is equal to $-mx^2$ )"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Plug in $x=1$ on the left side, and evaluate the limit on the right side:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ -m(1)^2 \\neq -(1)^3 + 2m $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ -m \\neq -1 + 2m $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ m \\neq \\frac{1}{3} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Since the limit exists at $x=1$, $^{\\lim}_{x \\to 1^{-}} (kx - 2) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 1^{+}} (-x^3 + 2m)$ must be true. Solve to get $k$ in terms of $m$:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ k(1) - 2 = -(1)^3 + 2m$"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ k = 1 + 2m$"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now, pick any value for $m$ such that $m \\neq \\frac{1}{3}$, and find $k$:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Take $m=1$:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ k = 1 + 2(1) = 3$"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Lastly, we must check to see if these values fit the question's needs"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 1^{-}} f(x) = ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 1} (kx - 2) = (3)(1) - 2 = 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 1^{+}} f(x) = ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 1} (-x^3+2m) = -(1)^3 + 2(1) = -1 + 2 = 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Therefore, the limit exists."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Also, $ f(1) = -(1)(1)^2 = -1 \\neq {\\lim}_{x \\to 1} f(x) $, so the function is discontinuous."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore m = 1 $ and $k=1$"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 6"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "For what values of $m$ and $b$ is the limit statement below true?"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {\\sqrt {mx + b} - 3} {x} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "First let's rationalize the limit:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {\\sqrt {mx + b} - 3} {x} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {(\\sqrt {mx + b} - 3)(\\sqrt {mx + b} + 3)} {x(\\sqrt {mx + b} + 3)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {mx + b - 9} {x(\\sqrt {mx + b} + 3)} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "We need to cancel out $x$ somehow. We can do so by setting $ b = 9 $ since $ 9 - 9 = 0 $, which allows us the cancel $x$:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {mx + (9) - 9} {x(\\sqrt {mx + b} + 3)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {mx} {x(\\sqrt {mx + b} + 3)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {m \\cancel {x}} {\\cancel {x} (\\sqrt {mx + 9} + 3)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {m} {\\sqrt {mx + 9} + 3} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now we need to solve the limit to get the value for $m$:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0} \\frac {m} {\\sqrt {mx + 9} + 3} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\frac {m} {\\sqrt {m(0) + 9} + 3} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\frac {m} {3 + 3} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 1 = \\frac {m} {6} \\ \\Rightarrow \\ m = 6  $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore $ The values $ b = 9 $ and $ m = 6 $ make the limit statement true."
  }
]
